                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 818.00/182</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Johnson</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-07-18T10:00:00-05:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 18, 1917, 10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to my cable of July 11, 11 p.m. Opposition to suspension of
                    constitutional guaranties or its equivalent continues. Measure <pb facs="0506"
                        n="340" xml:id="pg_340"/> still pending, likely to die or be rendered
                    harmless. Manifesto was issued by Tinoco same date warning against plots to
                    overthrow him. The document is a remarkable confession of weakness and
                    bankruptcy and regarded as poor judgment.</p>
                <p>Today is published legislative decree authorizing issue of 2,500,000 colones,
                    twelve year, twelve per cent bonds at ninety, secured by stamp tax, stamped
                    paper, mail and telegraph revenues.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
